  "prompt": "What exactly is 'pins and needles?",
  "response": "\"Pins and needles\" is a common sensation often described as a prickling, tingling, or numbness that typically occurs in a limb, such as an arm or leg. It is medically known as **paresthesia**. This sensation usually happens when pressure is applied to a nerve, temporarily disrupting its function. It\u2019s a temporary and harmless condition in most cases, but it can sometimes indicate an underlying issue.\n\n### Causes of Pins and Needles:\n1. **Pressure on Nerves**: Sitting or lying in one position for too long can compress nerves and restrict blood flow, leading to the sensation.\n2. **Nerve Compression**: Conditions like carpal tunnel syndrome or a herniated disc can compress nerves.\n3. **Poor Circulation**: Reduced blood flow to a limb can cause tingling.\n4. **Vitamin Deficiencies**: Deficiencies in vitamins like B12 or folate can affect nerve function.\n5. **Diabetes**: High blood sugar levels can damage nerves over time (neuropathy).\n6. **Injuries**: Nerve damage from injuries can cause paresthesia.\n7. **Other Medical Conditions**: Multiple sclerosis, stroke, or migraines can also be associated with pins and needles.\n\n### When to See a Doctor:\nWhile pins and needles are usually temporary and harmless, you should consult a healthcare professional if:\n- The sensation persists or worsens.\n- It occurs without an obvious cause.\n- It\u2019s accompanied by weakness, pain, or difficulty moving the affected limb.\n- It affects multiple parts of the body.\n\nIn most cases, the sensation resolves on its own once the pressure on the nerve is relieved or blood flow is restored. Stretching or changing positions can often help.",
